<font color="#FF0000">MOTIVES</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jun  5  6:23:34 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
     Motives  and emotions are very human feelings and you shouldn't be ashamed of questing the one and haveing the other.<br>
   Practical and cynical old me--I am well aware of the motives of business and I don't critize them, nor anyone else who wants to improve their situation.  It's natural and really, the &quot;American way&quot;---but just am aware  of their motives  AND then try to bend these &quot;natural&quot; motives to &quot;good ends.&quot;  An art---and we do need practice.<br>
     Hard to do perhaps, but if you can get those very bright--and self interested---people working toward YOUR ends, you have a hell of a good start on a perpetual motion machine.  <br>
   Of course you have to check that machine once in awhile.&lt;G&gt;<br><br>
&quot;If we could read the secret history of our enemies, <br>
        we should find in each one's life<br>
 sorrow and suffering enough to disarm all hostility.<br>
    Henry Wadsworth Longfellow, &quot;Driftwood&quot; 1857<br><br>
